aVThe most expensive home now for sale in the U.S. \u2013 $350 million \u2013 might look familiar. It was the Clampett family\u2019s mansion in the 1960s sitcom \u201cThe Beverly Hillbillies,\u201d Variety reported.\u000a\u000aEntirely changed and renovated since Uncle Jed, Jethro, Elly May and Granny, the Beverly Hills property was put on the market earlier this week following the death of owner A. Jerrold "Jerry" Perenchio, the Univision billionaire who died at 86, Time noted.\u000a\u000aPerenchio expanded the property \u2013 it now includes a former home of Ronald Reagan \u2013 and he brought in designer Henri Samuel, whose other clients included the Vanderbilts, Rothschilds and fashion designer Valentino, Money noted.\u000a\u000aThe Bel Air project reportedly took over four years to complete and a guided tour inside the house by CNBC\u2019s Robert Frank in the video below shows why.\u000a\u000aThe 38,000-square-foot mansion, standing four stories high, comprises 12 bedrooms and 21 bathrooms as well as three kitchens, six bars and various other nooks.\u000a\u000aThe game room contains a four-lane bowling alley with foosball and pool tables as well as a wall of candy dispensers.\u000a\u000aLocated adjacent to the entertainment area is an auto gallery containing $30 million dollars\u2019 worth of supercars and rare collectibles.\u000a\u000aThe house also contains a TV spanning nearly 30 feet, 130 pieces of art, and a stairway that cost $2 million dollars to build.\u000a\u000aOutside, the property features an 85-foot infinity pool, Jacuzzi and a 20-foot TV rising up in front of the pool.\u000a\u000aBruce Makowsky of Bam Luxury Group, developer of the house, said the property was situated in one of the best locations and offered an excellent view.\u000a\u000aAsked who might buy it, Makowsky said it would be somebody who wanted to enjoy life.\u000a\u000a\u201cThis is an ultimate party house, it\u2019s a home, and it\u2019s really comfortable,\u201d he said. \u201cIt has everything you have ever wanted inside the house including seven full-time staff to take care of you.\u201d\u000a\u000aMeet the man behind America's most expensive home from CNBC.\u000a\u000aRelated stories:
