aVNorth Korea has reached a "dead end" with its bullying nuclear threats and must realize the rest of the world has had enough of it, Sebastian Gorka, deputy assistant to President Donald Trump, told Newsmax TV on Monday.\u000a\u000a"The ball is in North Korea's court," Gorka said to Rita Cosby, guest host of Newsmax\u2019s "The Todd Schnitt Show."\u000a\u000a"They keep saying they're doing what they're doing for their national security when the reality is every one of these provocations undermine their security as much as anybody else's.\u000a\u000a"So the fact is they need to look in the mirror and understand that they have painted themselves into a corner and it is a dead end."\u000a\u000aImportant: Newsmax TV is available on DirecTV Ch. 349, U-Verse 1220, and FiOS 615. If your cable operator does not have Newsmax TV just call and ask them to put us on \u2013 Call toll-free 1-844-500-6397 and we will connect you right away to your cable operator!\u000a\u000aFor more places to Find Newsmax TV \u2013 Click Here Now\u000a\u000aEarly Monday, North Korea vowed to launch "thousands-fold" revenge against the U.S. after the U.N. imposed huge financial sanctions as punishment for recent intercontinental ballistic missile tests.\u000a\u000a"We're used to it. We're used to this nation that is more Stalinist than Josef Stalin, the Soviet Union ever was. But we're saddened," Gorka told Cosby.\u000a\u000a"Think about the significance of this. This is the most significant, largest sanctions package the international community has ever levied against North Korea.... [It] sends a very clear message, even Russia, even China, we have had enough. You are a menace and you are a great threat to international security."\u000a\u000aGorka, a counterinsurgency and counterterrorism expert and the author of "Defeating Jihad: The Winnable War," added: "Now it is up to Pyongyang to send a clear message that they understand they are going to stand down from their provocation and their escalatory behavior."
